        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix #86957: drain worker-spooled Telegram updates immediately",
        "body": "## Summary\n- Wake the Telegram isolated polling drain immediately after a worker-spooled update is written to `channel_ingress_events`.\n- Fix race condition: track pending drain requests while drain is active, run follow-up drain after active pass exits.\n- Add regression tests for both idle-drain and active-drain timing windows.\n- Keep the existing durable queue, claim, completion, and interval-drain behavior unchanged.\n\n## Issue\nFixes #86957.\n\n## Root Cause\nThe root source of this state lifecycle bug is that the isolated Telegram ingress worker asks the main polling session to write inbound updates into channel_ingress_events, but the main session only drained that spool at cycle start and on the periodic drain timer. Because the worker-write lifecycle did not wake the queue drain, a subsequent worker-spooled inbound update could remain pending until a later timer-driven drain.\n\n## Changes\n1. Added `requestImmediateDrain()` calls after worker write and spooled notification\n2. Added `drainRequested` flag to preserve wakeup requests during active drain\n3. Active drain runs a follow-up pass after exiting if a wakeup was requested\n4. Regression test for idle-drain wakeup (existing scenario)\n5. Regression test for active-drain wakeup (new scenario: worker writes during an active drain)\n\n## Verification\n- The fix adds `requestImmediateDrain()` calls in the update and spooled message handlers of the isolated ingress cycle.\n- A `drainRequested` flag records wakeups requested while `drainActive` is true; `drainOnce()` checks and runs a follow-up pass after the active pass exits.\n- Two regression tests with `drainIntervalMs: 60_000` verify both idle-drain and active-drain timing windows.",
